<p>Satellites, like digital cameras, record wavelengths. But they record a wider range of the electromagnetic spectrum. Different bands, like the RGB channels in the digital camera, that capture a certain range of wavelengths make up the satellite image.</p>

<p>But what interests the user: Health of a forest, surface temperature of Berlin, extent of flooding in Florida.</p>

<p>OpenSpaceData is trying to solve this challenge in two steps:</p>

<h2 id="1-the-acquisition-of-data-using-a-simple-search-mask">1. The acquisition of data using a simple search mask.</h2>

<p>For different jobs the measurement of different wavelengths of the elmag. Spectrum is necessary - e.g. water reflects a different wavelength than asphalt. But the user does not need to know this, because OpenSpaceData does that (choice of sensors, bands, wavelengths etc.). It translates the orders into the technical parameters necessary to retrieve the desired satellite data. The user receives the appropriate satellite image. However, this is not provided by OpenSpaceData, but is stored directly on an ESA server. The image can be easily downloaded via a link and then processed.</p>

<h2 id="2-einfache-anleitungen-zur-verarbeitung-der-daten">2. Einfache Anleitungen zur Verarbeitung der Daten</h2>

<p>Möchte man spezifische Werte wie den NDVI, der den Gesundheitszustand von Pflanzen von -1 bis +1 beschreibt, ermitteln, muss man verschiedene Bänder miteinander kombinieren. OpenSpaceData stellt einfache Anleitungen bereit, die angeben, wie und mit welchen Tools man die Bänder miteinander kombinieren kann, um den gewünschten Wert zu erhalten.</p>

<p>OpenSpaceData is an open source project. That means everything we develop is freely available for everyone to use and reuse - both the code and the content.</p>
